On the other hand, women only see abortion as their last resort, and they” drag the fact that they have committed abortion to their grave”.

According to the Global Times,

Just like the Chinese community in Taiwan, the Taiwanese community lived in Shanghai before the Second Sino-Japanese War. Many Chinese parents moved to Taiwan after the 1954 Martial Law and stigmatized abortion in their new homeland.

This only shows how Taiwan’s religious mindset hindered women from considering abortion as a strong option against a failing pregnancy.

In Taiwan, being pregnant is a taboo. Women should be ashamed of being pregnant outside some form of wedlock, which is why the reproductive rights of women have been suppressed for a long time in Taiwan.

Although the procedure is not illegal, the legislators are treating it as if it is a dangerous and a risky procedure.
